WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.350 --> 00:00:06.720
- Good morning, everyone.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:07.930
Delighted to have you here.

00:00:07.930 --> 00:00:08.680
I'm Liz Cohen.

00:00:08.680 --> 00:00:11.110
I'm Dean of the Radcliffe
institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:13.930
And I couldn't be more
pleased to welcome you

00:00:13.930 --> 00:00:17.650
to the Linda N. Cabot
Science Symposium entitled,

00:00:17.650 --> 00:00:21.590
"From Sea to Changing Sea--
a Science Symposium About

00:00:21.590 --> 00:00:22.700
Oceans."

00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:26.020
I'm especially pleased to see
so many members of the Radcliffe

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:29.910
Institute's Dean's Advisory
Council here today.

00:00:29.910 --> 00:00:33.490
I thank them, along with
our Radcliffe associates,

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:36.940
and many other faithful friends
of the Radcliffe Institute,

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:40.560
for your support
for all that we do.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.070
At the Radcliffe Institute
for Advanced Study,

00:00:43.070 --> 00:00:45.340
scholars, scientists,
and artists

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:49.650
work at the forefront of their
field and across disciplines.

00:00:49.650 --> 00:00:52.960
We are dedicated to
fostering and sharing

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:56.520
innovative work with the
public in all subjects.

00:00:56.520 --> 00:00:59.980
But we are especially proud
of our strong tradition

00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:03.720
in the sciences, a tradition
that manifests itself

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:07.210
in this annual science symposium
and in the related lecture

00:01:07.210 --> 00:01:10.930
series that runs throughout
the academic year.

00:01:10.930 --> 00:01:15.330
Science flourishes at Radcliffe
because of the many ways

00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:18.000
it intersects with
other disciplines.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.140
And we will certainly see
those intersections on display

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:24.450
here today at our
science symposium.

00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:27.800
We are very grateful for the
generosity of Linda Cabot

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:31.250
and her husband, Ed Anderson,
for their support of today's

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:35.460
symposium, and also for the way
that they embody the Radcliffe

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:37.360
mission.

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:41.720
Linda Cabot, Class of 1980,
is the founder and president

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:44.570
of an educational
organization dedicated

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:48.850
to inspiring the next
generation of ocean caretakers.

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:52.740
She is also a visual artist
and a lifelong sailor,

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:54.730
who brings both of
these perspectives

00:01:54.730 --> 00:01:58.880
to her love of the ocean,
just as we here at Radcliffe

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:01.080
bring a multi-disciplinary
approach

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:03.790
to many urgent subjects.

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:08.880
It is hard to imagine a more
urgent subject than oceans.

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:11.730
They cover three-quarters
of our planet,

00:02:11.730 --> 00:02:16.320
and supply 50% of the
oxygen we breathe.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:19.570
As Secretary of State
John Kerry said last month

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:22.970
at a conference on the ocean
hosted by the State Department,

00:02:22.970 --> 00:02:26.260
and I quote him, "Our
ocean is absolutely

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:28.630
essential for life itself.

00:02:28.630 --> 00:02:31.330
Not just the food, but
the oxygen and weather

00:02:31.330 --> 00:02:36.060
cycles of the planet
all depend on the ocean.

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:39.180
Throughout the world, the
sea sculpts the shorelines

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:42.400
of our continents, and
influences the changing

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:43.430
climate."

00:02:43.430 --> 00:02:49.000
Here in New England, the ocean
is especially inescapable.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.760
The coastline is literally
right at our doorstep.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:58.070
So concerns about rising sea
levels hit very close to home.

00:02:58.070 --> 00:03:01.340
Scientists predict that
sea levels in Boston

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:04.490
could rise anywhere
from two to six feet

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:06.630
by the end of the century.

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:10.490
Our doorsteps, in other words,
are the very ones the rising

00:03:10.490 --> 00:03:13.060
seas are going to flood.

00:03:13.060 --> 00:03:17.070
But the ocean shapes far
more than our landscape here

00:03:17.070 --> 00:03:18.200
in New England.

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:22.360
It undergirds our economy,
shapes our culture.

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:24.540
It inspires our urban planning.

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:28.040
It influences public
health, and much more.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:32.440
So when we say that the ocean
has an impact on climate

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:37.070
change, we mean the economic
and cultural climates as well as

00:03:37.070 --> 00:03:38.380
the natural one.

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:40.820
Let me give you some examples.

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:44.980
Cod was once so plentiful
off the coast of New England

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:49.140
that fisherman joked that they
could walk across the Atlantic

00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:51.480
on the backs of this
ubiquitous fish,

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:54.100
and never get their feet wet.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:57.420
Now cod populations
have collapsed,

00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:01.300
partly because of overfishing,
but also because of the rising

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:04.900
temperatures of New
England's coastal waters.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:09.200
In fact, the cod catch
has declined by fully 90%

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:11.370
over the past three decades.

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:15.770
One of our speakers today will
address this critical question.

00:04:15.770 --> 00:04:18.200
At the same time,
warmer waters have

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:22.930
led to increases in stocks of
shellfish, including lobster.

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:26.550
More lobster might
sound like good news,

00:04:26.550 --> 00:04:30.430
until we realize that the
sudden increase in supply

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:33.250
can make wholesale
prices plummet.

00:04:33.250 --> 00:04:37.440
In 2012, the price paid
to lobstering crews

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:42.150
fell to $2 per pound, compared
to the more typical rate

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:43.830
of $4 per pound.

00:04:43.830 --> 00:04:47.190
And it caused real
economic hardship.

00:04:47.190 --> 00:04:49.990
One specific place where
shifts in the ocean

00:04:49.990 --> 00:04:53.730
have ripple effects on the
local economy and culture

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:56.910
is the town of Chatham
on Cape Cod, site

00:04:56.910 --> 00:04:59.220
of the Monomoy Wildlife Refuge.

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:01.900
Tides, storms, and
rising sea levels

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:04.990
have redrawn the
boundaries of the Refuge.

00:05:04.990 --> 00:05:09.090
US Fish and Wildlife Service
has responded with a wildlife

00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:12.690
management plan that
Chatham town officials

00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:15.770
and Massachusetts attorney
general Maura Healy

00:05:15.770 --> 00:05:18.840
say will threaten
the fishing economy.

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:22.340
Meanwhile, after generations
of careful stewardship,

00:05:22.340 --> 00:05:25.570
fishing families perceive
the outside restrictions

00:05:25.570 --> 00:05:28.360
as an attack on local identity.

00:05:28.360 --> 00:05:31.880
In short, oceans shape
our world and our lives

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:33.750
in very real ways.

00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:35.890
If we want to
understand the ocean,

00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:39.130
then we need to look at it from
many different perspectives,

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:42.420
which is exactly what we
are going to do here today.

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:45.030
Scholars and experts
on subjects ranging

00:05:45.030 --> 00:05:48.420
from evolutionary
biology to oceanography

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.950
will be sharing the stage with
public officials, a Coast Guard

00:05:51.950 --> 00:05:54.560
officer, and a law professor.

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:56.140
Today's conference
has been argued

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:59.570
organized by John Huth, the
Donner Professor of Science

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:02.880
at Harvard, and Faculty Director
for the Physical Sciences

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.690
at the Radcliffe Institute.

00:06:04.690 --> 00:06:08.710
I want to thank John
for putting together

00:06:08.710 --> 00:06:11.480
such a probing and
fascinating day for us.

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:14.570
He is the ideal leader
for a Radcliffe conference

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:18.340
about oceans, because so
many of John's professional

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:21.550
and personal interests
have to do with the water.

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:23.740
He is a physicist
who has written

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:27.620
about the science of navigation
from the shores of New England

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:29.300
to the Marshall Islands.

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:33.600
And he is an expert kayaker,
who is as comfortable in a boat

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:35.660
as he is in a computer lab.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:38.746
So please join me now
in welcoming John Huth.

00:06:38.746 --> 00:06:43.990
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:43.990 --> 00:06:45.080
- Thanks, Liz.

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:47.580
So welcome to everybody,
and good morning.

00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:49.590
I think we have an
exciting program that

00:06:49.590 --> 00:06:53.540
will be very informative,
and you'll enjoy it.

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.150
So let me just frame
my own interest,

00:06:56.150 --> 00:06:58.530
and how I came to set this up.

00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:03.140
As part of my explorations
of how people navigate,

00:07:03.140 --> 00:07:07.580
I went to the Marshall
Islands, and went on a voyage

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:10.580
with an outrigger canoe
between two of the atolls.

00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:13.440
And we ended up on the
island of Tabal, which

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:16.320
is on the remote atoll of Aur.

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:21.680
And there, we were greeted with
flower garlands and a feast,

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:25.620
where we had all of these fish,
and breadfruit, and lobsters,

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:26.710
and crabs.

00:07:26.710 --> 00:07:30.340
And we were welcomed
with open arms.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:34.330
In a sense the people who we
were coming with and visiting

00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:36.410
were trying to revive the
culture in the Marshall

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:40.720
Islands, which is under a
tremendous amount of stress,

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:44.870
both from colonial powers,
but also from the encroaching

00:07:44.870 --> 00:07:46.930
oceans as the sea levels rise.

00:07:46.930 --> 00:07:50.330
And what might have been
an abstract thought prior

00:07:50.330 --> 00:07:53.620
to my visit there
became quite visceral--

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:56.160
how their lives were
inextricably linked

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.620
with the oceans.

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:59.300
And this hit home.

00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:03.360
And what I realized when
I got back to the States

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:07.540
was that we, indeed-- our
fates are inextricably linked

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:10.300
to the oceans, and we
come from the oceans.

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:13.230
And we also put a lot
of stress on the oceans.

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:16.330
So as part of the
Radcliffe duties,

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:18.670
I suppose-- I'd hardly
call them duties anymore,

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:22.100
because it's so enjoyable to
work here-- I put together

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:24.780
this Science Symposium on
Oceans, which gave me something

00:08:24.780 --> 00:08:27.650
of a hunting license to
explore a set of topics

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:30.580
that I found to be at
the frontiers of science,

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:32.240
but also fascinating.

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:35.490
And in trying to find
these speakers that you'll

00:08:35.490 --> 00:08:40.390
hear today, I realized
how incredibly complex

00:08:40.390 --> 00:08:43.480
the oceans are, and
the diversity of things

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:44.680
you find in the oceans.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:46.030
It's just unbelievable.

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:49.690
So I'm grateful for the
speakers that we have today,

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:51.540
and I welcome you.

00:08:51.540 --> 00:08:56.100
I also want to thank Linda
Cabot for supporting us in this.

00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:58.470
She's done a fantastic
job and provided me

00:08:58.470 --> 00:09:01.700
with a lot of insight, too,
in conservation of the oceans.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:03.260
So I'm grateful for that.

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:06.350
So let me invite our
first panel today.

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:09.170
It's going to talk about early
life, and interesting life

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:09.760
in the ocean.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:13.581
So we have Chris,
Peter, and David coming.

00:09:13.581 --> 00:09:15.330
You can take your seats
now, and I'll just

00:09:15.330 --> 00:09:17.950
say a few introductory words.

00:09:17.950 --> 00:09:21.160
So to frame this
a little bit, we

00:09:21.160 --> 00:09:25.280
had a recent talk on the
search for life on exoplanets.

00:09:25.280 --> 00:09:29.190
And the speaker talked about
looking for signatures of life

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:32.080
that more or less are kind
of our conventional ideas

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:37.560
of what life might be like--
carbon-emitting creatures

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:39.550
and certain ratios of
gases that we would see.

00:09:39.550 --> 00:09:43.520
But it was very much tied to
a conventional view of life

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:44.190
as we know it.

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:45.689
And people were
asking the question,

00:09:45.689 --> 00:09:47.130
what about other forms of life?

00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:48.921
And the speaker said,
well, we can't really

00:09:48.921 --> 00:09:52.060
imagine other forms of life
than the conventional sorts

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:53.220
of things.

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:55.980
And it's difficult to imagine
what the origins of life

00:09:55.980 --> 00:10:00.440
might have been in an
earlier epoch in our planet.

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:02.300
But then you start to
scratch the surface,

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:05.010
and you look at people that
study different forms of life.

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:07.740
And you realize that there are
some amazing forms of life that

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:10.070
don't really conform to
our normal visions of what

00:10:10.070 --> 00:10:11.610
they might be in the oceans.

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:14.200
And so what I tried to do
was assemble some speakers

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:15.920
that could talk to that.

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:18.180
So with little
further ado, I'm going

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:21.330
to introduce Chris
Bowler, who we're

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:23.750
grateful to have as a Radcliffe
Fellow here this year,

00:10:23.750 --> 00:10:27.230
who just kind of spoke up at
one of our initial meetings.

00:10:27.230 --> 00:10:30.460
And immediately, I was
able to start digging

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:31.470
up some information.

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:33.090
And the wheels started turning.

00:10:33.090 --> 00:10:40.650
He is a director of the
CRNS Institute for Biology,

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:44.900
and Professor at L'Ecole
Superieure in Paris,

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:50.477
and works on phytoplanktons,
and amazing to talk to.

00:10:50.477 --> 00:10:52.588
Chris.

00:10:52.588 --> 00:10:55.432
[APPLAUSE]

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:01.150
- Great, well, thank you, John.

00:11:01.150 --> 00:11:03.180
It's great to be here.

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:07.330
Yes, as John mentioned, I'm
based in Paris, normally.

00:11:07.330 --> 00:11:11.050
But I'm on sabbatical here
at the Radcliffe Institute

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:12.440
as a fellow for this year.

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:17.480
And it's a wonderful
opportunity to meet many people,

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:21.470
and to explore new avenues
of research, and so on.

00:11:21.470 --> 00:11:27.480
And it's great to see,
also, that the ocean is

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:32.970
receiving so much interest in
the US, as it is in Europe.

00:11:32.970 --> 00:11:35.260
We've had a lot of talks,
a lot of discussions,

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:37.770
about the importance of
the ocean, a lot of concern

00:11:37.770 --> 00:11:40.180
about the ocean in
Europe, and it's

00:11:40.180 --> 00:11:45.010
great to see the same sort of
concern over here in the USA,

00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:46.740
too.

00:11:46.740 --> 00:11:51.920
So without further ado, I'll
introduce the first session,

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:54.330
which is entitled, "Early
Life in the Oceans,"

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:57.670
which is a really
important topic,

00:11:57.670 --> 00:12:02.520
obviously, because everything
that is in the ocean to date

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:04.970
came from this early
life in the ocean.

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:07.290
In fact, everything--
all life on Earth--

00:12:07.290 --> 00:12:12.560
evolved from the ocean three and
a half billion or so years ago.

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:16.070
So we're all evolved from
these little organisms

00:12:16.070 --> 00:12:21.270
which started the process
of life on this planet.

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:23.470
So it's a fascinating topic.

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:25.480
We've got two great
speakers here,

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:28.090
who will introduce their
research on the topic.

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:29.590
We'll have two
talks, and then we'll

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:32.640
have a discussion time
with questions and answers,

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:33.190
and so on.

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:36.740
So please save your
questions until the end.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:41.250
And so the first speaker
is David Emerson,

00:12:41.250 --> 00:12:44.690
who is Senior Research
Scientist and Associate

00:12:44.690 --> 00:12:50.160
Director for Bacteriology in
the Bigelow Laboratory for Ocean

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:54.320
Sciences, which is a very, very
well-known institute worldwide,

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:57.090
and also has a very,
very important culture

00:12:57.090 --> 00:13:01.800
collection of microorganisms
from the ocean.

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:04.900
That is a very, very important
resource for scientists

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:06.590
throughout the world.

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:09.240
So thank you for being
part of this institute,

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:11.060
and for the work you do.

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:14.286
And I'll hand it over to you.

00:13:14.286 --> 00:13:19.252
[APPLAUSE]

00:13:19.252 --> 00:13:21.710
- Thanks very much, Chris, for
that very nice introduction.

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:24.990
It's really terrific to
be here, to be leading off

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:26.100
this symposium.

00:13:26.100 --> 00:13:29.590
I'm really excited to have
the opportunity to do this.

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:31.210
We had a wonderful
dinner last night

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:33.030
at Dean Cohen's residence.

00:13:33.030 --> 00:13:37.130
It was really amazing to
learn about the Radcliffe

00:13:37.130 --> 00:13:40.510
Institution, and appreciate
everything they do,

00:13:40.510 --> 00:13:45.330
and especially Linda Cabot
for supporting this symposium.

