Want to give it a go?

00:55:47.140 --> 00:55:48.140
Do you want me to start?

00:55:48.140 --> 00:55:48.320
Yeah.

00:55:48.320 --> 00:55:49.110
By all means.

00:55:49.110 --> 00:55:51.980
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:51.980 --> 00:55:52.980
The expert's right here.

00:55:55.630 --> 00:55:56.860
That was not my intention.

00:55:56.860 --> 00:56:00.510
Well, you're up here.

00:56:00.510 --> 00:56:02.102
Yeah, I didn't
prepare an answer.

00:56:02.102 --> 00:56:03.310
I just prepared the question.

00:56:06.649 --> 00:56:14.350
So certainly one thing, we know
that oxygenic photosynthesis

00:56:14.350 --> 00:56:16.970
evolved as we saw this morning.

00:56:16.970 --> 00:56:21.250
And that subsequent to that,
respiration sort of evolved.

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:26.260
And respiration is
photosynthesis in reverse.

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:32.030
So rather than consuming
CO2 and generating oxygen,

00:56:32.030 --> 00:56:36.210
respiration is consuming
oxygen and generating CO2.

00:56:36.210 --> 00:56:38.590
So this happened at some point.

00:56:38.590 --> 00:56:41.410
And then subsequent
to that, there

00:56:41.410 --> 00:56:45.160
was the evolution of
the eukaryotes, what

00:56:45.160 --> 00:56:47.190
Dave talked about
with the prokaryotes--

00:56:47.190 --> 00:56:52.250
the primitive bacteria
and Archaea organisms.

00:56:52.250 --> 00:56:54.750
Subsequently to those,
we had the eukaryotes,

00:56:54.750 --> 00:56:59.290
which are more complex
cells-- the sorts of cells

00:56:59.290 --> 00:57:02.880
that we have, where
we have respiration

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:06.860
happening inside mitochondria,
which used to be bacteria

00:57:06.860 --> 00:57:09.540
that we acquired.

00:57:09.540 --> 00:57:14.920
And the photosynthetic
organisms took the cyanobacteria

00:57:14.920 --> 00:57:17.390
inside the cells, and
generated the chloroplasts,

00:57:17.390 --> 00:57:20.310
which power photosynthesis now.

00:57:20.310 --> 00:57:25.240
So we had the evolution of
the eukaryotic organisms--

00:57:25.240 --> 00:57:29.070
unicellular, still.

00:57:29.070 --> 00:57:33.730
And then I don't really
know too much more.

00:57:33.730 --> 00:57:37.510
Those may be the evolution
of some fairly primitive

00:57:37.510 --> 00:57:42.370
multicellular life forms, not
very complex, not very well

00:57:42.370 --> 00:57:45.480
developed, which then
subsequently gave birth

00:57:45.480 --> 00:57:49.680
to the incredible explosion
of multi-cellular life

00:57:49.680 --> 00:57:50.460
in the Cambrian.

00:57:50.460 --> 00:57:53.300
So I wonder how that happened.

00:57:53.300 --> 00:57:59.530
I think I had the privilege
of teaching a course a couple

00:57:59.530 --> 00:58:01.040
of years ago with Andy Knoll.

00:58:01.040 --> 00:58:03.690
And one of the things
that we really tried to do

00:58:03.690 --> 00:58:08.820
is step away from
concerning ourselves

00:58:08.820 --> 00:58:12.890
about the particular organisms
that evolved over time,

00:58:12.890 --> 00:58:15.460
and focus on this sort
of fundamental question.

00:58:15.460 --> 00:58:18.210
And I think Chris, you
set this up really well,

00:58:18.210 --> 00:58:21.472
in that as we think about
the evolution of life

00:58:21.472 --> 00:58:23.430
and the evolution of the
eucaryotes-- actually,

00:58:23.430 --> 00:58:26.420
let's go back to respiration.

00:58:26.420 --> 00:58:30.850
Once we start to see the
evolution of eukaryotes that

00:58:30.850 --> 00:58:37.105
have in them what was likely
a bacteria that now came

00:58:37.105 --> 00:58:38.480
inside another
cell, and you have

00:58:38.480 --> 00:58:41.280
a cell with this
mitochondria, which

00:58:41.280 --> 00:58:44.410
are your power
plants in your body,

00:58:44.410 --> 00:58:46.970
you have an organism
that's carrying out

00:58:46.970 --> 00:58:48.170
aerobic respiration.

00:58:48.170 --> 00:58:50.980
And from the physiologist's
point of view,

00:58:50.980 --> 00:58:52.530
one thing that's
neat to think about

00:58:52.530 --> 00:58:57.800
is how much energy you get
from different substrates

00:58:57.800 --> 00:58:59.510
that you might use.

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:01.830
And so Dave talked a lot
about iron oxidizers.

00:59:01.830 --> 00:59:04.320
And if you start
looking at the energy

00:59:04.320 --> 00:59:08.810
yield you can get from oxidizing
iron with oxygen, or nitrate,

00:59:08.810 --> 00:59:10.980
or something else, you
get a certain amount

00:59:10.980 --> 00:59:13.360
of energy per mole.

00:59:13.360 --> 00:59:15.580
Or think of it as
like how much energy

00:59:15.580 --> 00:59:18.700
do you get from eating a dozen
eggs versus a dozen celery

00:59:18.700 --> 00:59:19.940
sticks?

00:59:19.940 --> 00:59:22.930
The eggs are going to have
a lot more energy per unit.

00:59:22.930 --> 00:59:26.470
And when we think about
energy metabolism,

00:59:26.470 --> 00:59:30.410
respiration is an incredible
way to get a lot of energy

00:59:30.410 --> 00:59:31.460
per unit substrate.

00:59:31.460 --> 00:59:33.470
And this opens up a
lot of possibilities.

00:59:33.470 --> 00:59:35.430
And it's, I would argue,
one of the factors

00:59:35.430 --> 00:59:39.100
why we see the evolution
of multicellularity.

00:59:39.100 --> 00:59:41.360
The punchline, in a way,
comes down to this--

00:59:41.360 --> 00:59:44.670
that all of the diversity of
animal life you see on Earth

00:59:44.670 --> 00:59:49.650
is based to a lesser extent
on the differences in energy

00:59:49.650 --> 00:59:50.650
metabolism.

00:59:50.650 --> 00:59:53.580
Because how you make your energy
is frankly, not that different

00:59:53.580 --> 00:59:58.030
than a goldfish, or a leopard,
or a snake, or a lizard.

00:59:58.030 --> 01:00:02.610
All of those organisms--
we all eat organic matter.

01:00:02.610 --> 01:00:05.730
I don't mean Whole Foods,
I mean organic matter.

01:00:05.730 --> 01:00:08.896
And we breathe
oxygen. And that's

01:00:08.896 --> 01:00:10.020
how we generate our energy.

01:00:10.020 --> 01:00:10.816
And that's it.

01:00:10.816 --> 01:00:12.940
You can hold your breath
and do some amount of work

01:00:12.940 --> 01:00:14.480
for some time, but that's it.

01:00:14.480 --> 01:00:17.860
Microbes have this tremendous
physiological diversity.

01:00:17.860 --> 01:00:20.890
Some of them seem to get
energy from oxidizing uranium.

01:00:20.890 --> 01:00:23.800
I mean, it's out of
control what microbes do.

01:00:23.800 --> 01:00:26.590
But we organisms, we get
our energy by eating things.

01:00:26.590 --> 01:00:28.500
And it's led to this
tremendous diversity

01:00:28.500 --> 01:00:30.500
of morphological adaptations.

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:34.030
We see all these kinds of
multicellular life having

01:00:34.030 --> 01:00:36.430
very different shapes,
and different forms, that

01:00:36.430 --> 01:00:38.250
capitalizes on our environment.

01:00:38.250 --> 01:00:40.206
And so I think that
isn't necessarily

01:00:40.206 --> 01:00:41.830
what happened over
that period of time.

01:00:41.830 --> 01:00:43.530
But once you get
respiration, and you

01:00:43.530 --> 01:00:45.510
start to get
eukaryotes, you do start

01:00:45.510 --> 01:00:48.930
to see this diversification
of multicellularity.

01:00:48.930 --> 01:00:50.680
Excellent.

01:00:50.680 --> 01:00:53.180
So maybe I could just add a
little genetic touch to that.

01:00:56.810 --> 01:01:01.600
So the microbes that Pete
talked about as being incredible

01:01:01.600 --> 01:01:04.180
abundance, well, that
genetic diversity is also

01:01:04.180 --> 01:01:05.220
incredibly abundant.

01:01:05.220 --> 01:01:08.000
And all of our genes
are somehow derived

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:12.340
from a microbial ancestor,
and the gene for using oxygen.

01:01:12.340 --> 01:01:14.300
Pete and I are looking
at trying to-- one

01:01:14.300 --> 01:01:17.120
of the things we're interested
in is trying to measure how low

01:01:17.120 --> 01:01:21.540
a microbe can go in terms of its
ability to respire on oxygen.

01:01:21.540 --> 01:01:24.750
But it was the development
of those processes,

01:01:24.750 --> 01:01:28.760
and that genetic
adaptations, that ultimately

01:01:28.760 --> 01:01:31.271
led to multicellular life.

01:01:31.271 --> 01:01:32.770
And I think that's
a great question,

01:01:32.770 --> 01:01:40.370
is can we see those ancestral
gene exchange events,

01:01:40.370 --> 01:01:44.740
even, to try to
track that process.

