And it's a lot of water.

01:05:38.330 --> 01:05:45.450
But you know that the moon of
Europa, the moon of Jupiter,

01:05:45.450 --> 01:05:48.820
has an ocean that's twice the
volume of the earth's ocean?

01:05:48.820 --> 01:05:51.070
But it's under 20
kilometers of ice.

01:05:51.070 --> 01:05:53.780
So think about that.

01:05:53.780 --> 01:05:55.880
OK, next question, please.

01:05:55.880 --> 01:05:57.920
David Jackson,
Radcliffe Institute.

01:06:00.980 --> 01:06:04.940
Doctor Emerson was alluding
to genetic processes

01:06:04.940 --> 01:06:09.340
are very important in the
evolution of oceans and things

01:06:09.340 --> 01:06:10.320
that live in them.

01:06:10.320 --> 01:06:11.778
I wonder if you
could say something

01:06:11.778 --> 01:06:15.050
about the role of viruses,
which more and more are being

01:06:15.050 --> 01:06:19.450
discovered daily in the
oceans, both as agents

01:06:19.450 --> 01:06:23.480
for genetic exchange, and
as natural selective agents

01:06:23.480 --> 01:06:25.104
in their own right.

01:06:29.280 --> 01:06:32.866
You showed the picture of the
microbes strung [INAUDIBLE].

01:06:32.866 --> 01:06:34.490
How far do the viruses go?

01:06:34.490 --> 01:06:37.960
Yeah, exactly, that's probably
another astronomical number.

01:06:37.960 --> 01:06:42.240
So just to provide
a bit of context--

01:06:42.240 --> 01:06:46.480
so viruses can play a
role in moving genes

01:06:46.480 --> 01:06:48.150
from one organism to another.

01:06:48.150 --> 01:06:51.540
And one of the challenges we
have in thinking about microbes

01:06:51.540 --> 01:06:54.280
is that there seems to be
a degree of promiscuity

01:06:54.280 --> 01:06:56.320
among microbes in their genes.

01:06:56.320 --> 01:06:59.190
That is, we see genes from one
microbe in another microbe.

01:06:59.190 --> 01:07:01.480
This is also true
in animals, where

01:07:01.480 --> 01:07:05.830
we start to see genes in animals
and microbes, and vice versa.

01:07:05.830 --> 01:07:11.030
And so I think it
is absolutely fair

01:07:11.030 --> 01:07:16.390
to say that our community's
ongoing studies of viruses,

01:07:16.390 --> 01:07:18.420
or the so-called
virome, is going

01:07:18.420 --> 01:07:20.090
to show that they
play a tremendous role

01:07:20.090 --> 01:07:24.000
in the evolution of microbes
on Earth, and animals as well.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:29.240
And so this, to me, really
challenges our notion

01:07:29.240 --> 01:07:33.760
of the species concept, which is
robust in the absence of that.

01:07:33.760 --> 01:07:37.880
But then, if we find out,
for example, that you, sir,

01:07:37.880 --> 01:07:41.770
are 3% algae-- I'm being
ridiculous-- but then

01:07:41.770 --> 01:07:43.110
what does that mean?

01:07:43.110 --> 01:07:46.460
And so a lot of work is being
put into studying viruses,

01:07:46.460 --> 01:07:48.990
not only in the open
ocean, but actually,

01:07:48.990 --> 01:07:52.520
in the deep subsurface
biosphere as well, where

01:07:52.520 --> 01:07:54.560
we know that there are
tremendous communities

01:07:54.560 --> 01:07:57.180
of microbes, and are trying to
understand the role of viruses

01:07:57.180 --> 01:07:58.175
in mediating exchange.

01:08:00.830 --> 01:08:02.970
Just one quick
addition to that--

01:08:02.970 --> 01:08:06.620
it's estimated by my colleagues
at Bigelow, some of whom

01:08:06.620 --> 01:08:09.590
are virologists, that basically,
all these phytoplankton

01:08:09.590 --> 01:08:14.850
you see on the walls here could
turn over almost every day,

01:08:14.850 --> 01:08:16.824
just due to virolysis as well.

01:08:16.824 --> 01:08:17.490
Oh, yeah, right.

01:08:17.490 --> 01:08:20.760
Just an incredibly important
process in terms of the carbon

01:08:20.760 --> 01:08:22.910
cycle in the ocean.

01:08:22.910 --> 01:08:25.430
So don't think of
viruses as just nasty,

01:08:25.430 --> 01:08:29.660
disease-causing things, but more
like lubricants in the ocean,

01:08:29.660 --> 01:08:32.350
making sure that the
ecosystem is turning over

01:08:32.350 --> 01:08:37.810
and gene flow and [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:37.810 --> 01:08:40.140
Next question, please.

01:08:40.140 --> 01:08:45.590
I am Prudence Steiner on the
Radcliffe Institute board.

01:08:45.590 --> 01:08:49.460
I have perhaps the most
naive question of all.

01:08:49.460 --> 01:08:51.719
And that is, how
do you define life?

01:08:54.817 --> 01:08:56.775
And by the way, I'm not
thinking theologically.

01:09:01.640 --> 01:09:03.479
One of those naive
questions [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:03.479 --> 01:09:05.069
Let's dump it on Chris again.

01:09:05.069 --> 01:09:05.569
Chris?

01:09:09.910 --> 01:09:14.510
Virus is not considered to be
living organisms, for example.

01:09:14.510 --> 01:09:19.580
So in our definition of life,
viruses are not in there.

01:09:19.580 --> 01:09:24.420
So then, they're not in there
because they are not self

01:09:24.420 --> 01:09:25.359
replicating.

01:09:25.359 --> 01:09:28.189
They need other
things to replicate.

01:09:28.189 --> 01:09:31.410
So yeah, once you cross that
border, that a virus isn't

01:09:31.410 --> 01:09:35.680
life, then where do you go?

01:09:35.680 --> 01:09:37.830
It's hard.

01:09:42.200 --> 01:09:45.310
You have to be able
to generate energy.

01:09:45.310 --> 01:09:48.256
You have to be able to
reproduce, replicate.

01:09:48.256 --> 01:09:53.040
I'd say those are-- and I
was just at the NASA workshop

01:09:53.040 --> 01:09:54.990
where we were discussing
some of these issues.

01:09:54.990 --> 01:09:58.530
And one of the issues that
came up was being able to move,

01:09:58.530 --> 01:10:03.180
being mobile, being able to
move is another potentially very

01:10:03.180 --> 01:10:04.770
important thing for life.

01:10:04.770 --> 01:10:05.970
Because you can move around.

01:10:05.970 --> 01:10:09.360
And to move, you
can eat in one spot.

01:10:09.360 --> 01:10:11.600
But if you can't
move somewhere else,

01:10:11.600 --> 01:10:14.995
then you consume
all your resources.

01:10:14.995 --> 01:10:16.370
And yet, of course,
we know there

01:10:16.370 --> 01:10:17.620
are organisms that don't move.

01:10:17.620 --> 01:10:19.160
I mean, it's a tough one.

01:10:19.160 --> 01:10:22.020
And this is of great interest
to the astrobiology community,

01:10:22.020 --> 01:10:26.150
because if we start looking for
life on other planetary bodies,

01:10:26.150 --> 01:10:29.420
the question is, do you
look for things like DNA?

01:10:29.420 --> 01:10:32.770
Well, you might not find
the same core molecules.

01:10:32.770 --> 01:10:36.374
And there may be other metrics
we need to put into place.

01:10:36.374 --> 01:10:37.190
Thank you.

01:10:37.190 --> 01:10:39.500
My name is Davidson
[? Reuben, ?] a student

01:10:39.500 --> 01:10:40.880
at Harvard.

01:10:40.880 --> 01:10:44.980
I'm curious as to-- this is
directed at Professor Peter

01:10:44.980 --> 01:10:52.150
Girguis-- given-- I'm not as
courageous as the previous

01:10:52.150 --> 01:10:55.220
questioner to ask the question.

01:10:55.220 --> 01:10:58.380
Given that there's not
been as much research

01:10:58.380 --> 01:11:00.620
as we've explored in
other fields, such just

01:11:00.620 --> 01:11:03.760
space and terrestrial
planes, what

01:11:03.760 --> 01:11:09.590
does the data give so far as to
what our oceans might become?

01:11:09.590 --> 01:11:12.635
As we've previously seen, it's
not going to be eradicated.

01:11:12.635 --> 01:11:14.010
It's not going to
be annihilated.

01:11:14.010 --> 01:11:18.740
So would it more favor
aerobic organisms,

01:11:18.740 --> 01:11:22.760
or will anaerobic organisms
grow in multitude?

01:11:22.760 --> 01:11:25.380
What would be the effects that
we see from the current data?

01:11:25.380 --> 01:11:27.410
Thank you.

01:11:27.410 --> 01:11:30.480
So Davidson's a
students in my class,

01:11:30.480 --> 01:11:33.231
by the way, so this is
definitely an extra credit

01:11:33.231 --> 01:11:33.730
point.

01:11:37.294 --> 01:11:39.710
So in the interest of time,
Davidson, I'll keep it simple,

01:11:39.710 --> 01:11:41.910
and say that I suspect our
speakers this afternoon are

01:11:41.910 --> 01:11:43.326
going to touch
upon a lot of that.

01:11:43.326 --> 01:11:45.030
So we'll let them do
the heavy lifting.

01:11:45.030 --> 01:11:48.370
But I think it's more
than just the simple idea

01:11:48.370 --> 01:11:49.950
of, oh, the temperature
might change,

01:11:49.950 --> 01:11:51.380
or oxygen might be less.

01:11:51.380 --> 01:11:54.140
Because those all have
subsequent consequences.

01:11:54.140 --> 01:11:58.950
If temperature changes enough,
and we disrupt the global ocean

01:11:58.950 --> 01:12:02.170
circulation, that
has huge implications

01:12:02.170 --> 01:12:05.500
for the distribution of
oxygen and other components.

01:12:05.500 --> 01:12:08.690
And so I'll leave it to our
speakers this afternoon.

01:12:08.690 --> 01:12:11.191
But that's the tough part.

01:12:11.191 --> 01:12:12.690
There is no crystal
ball that we can

01:12:12.690 --> 01:12:14.880
look into that says, oh,
it's as simple as this.

01:12:14.880 --> 01:12:16.570
We really don't
know, in my opinion.

01:12:19.720 --> 01:12:22.120
OK, well, if there's
